  "opinion": "As a self-employed electrician in Chicago with a vocational diploma and a background shaped by both academic and hands-on learning, I've seen firsthand how stereotypes can linger in technical fields. Stereotype threat—the anxiety that your group is labeled as less capable—can silently sabotage potential in STEM. For instance, when I’ve worked with young people who’ve grown up hearing 'you’re not cut out for engineering,' that fear can make them avoid challenging problems. It’s not just about the words; it’s about the quiet erosion of confidence. We absolutely should address this, but not with top-down policies that ignore real-world experience. Instead, we need to build environments where everyone feels seen and capable from the start. At my shop, I’ve started by sharing stories of how my own journey—facing doubts as a kid in a neighborhood where college wasn’t the norm—helped me find my footing. That kind of relatable storytelling, paired with hands-on projects that let kids apply math and physics without the pressure of exams, works better than lectures. I believe in practical, community-driven solutions: mentorship that focuses on real-world skills, inclusive workshops that welcome all backgrounds, and celebrating diverse paths to technical success. The key is to make learning feel like a natural extension of what people already do, not something they’re 'expected' to do. After all, every person has a unique way of solving problems—whether it’s through the precision of an electric circuit or the creativity of a painting. Let’s stop letting stereotypes hold us back and start building bridges where everyone’s strengths can shine.",
